# What is a Token?

A token is the **smallest unit of text** that an LLM processes.

A token may be

- A word
- Part of a word
- A punctuation mark
- A number
- A space (in some tokenizers)
- A special symbol

The important point is:

> **LLMs do not understand words directly. They understand tokens.**
Many tokenizers include leading spaces as part of the token.
Unbeliveable---> Because those smaller pieces appear frequently during training and help the model generalize.


Why don't LLMs simply read words?
LLMs don't read words directly because a word-level vocabulary would become extremely large and couldn't efficiently handle new or rare words.
Many words also share common parts, such as 'play', 'playing', and 'played', so using subword tokens lets the model reuse those patterns. 
The tokenizer converts text into subword tokens, maps them to token IDs, and then to embeddings, which the Transformer processes.
This approach reduces vocabulary size, handles unseen words better, and improves efficiency.


"How do LLMs handle unseen words?"

"The tokenizer has a fixed vocabulary learned during training. When it encounters a word that isn't in that vocabulary, it doesn't create a new token. 
Instead, it splits the word into known subword tokens using its learned tokenization algorithm, such as BPE, and maps those existing subwords to their existing token IDs.
This allows the model to process new or rare words without expanding its vocabulary."



[Every tokenizer has a fixed vocabulary. Each token has a unique ID.]****
LLMs actually process these IDs internally, not the text itself.

The model now sees -- 123,678,99--instead of the original words.

Why can't an LLM process plain English directly?
Because neural networks perform mathematical operations on numbers, not text. Therefore, text must first be converted into tokens and then into numerical representations before the model can process it.

What is a Token?

A token is the smallest unit of text that a language model processes. 
Before an LLM understands language, it breaks the input into tokens, converts them into numerical representations, and then processes them to predict the next token.

Key Takeaways
A token is the smallest unit processed by an LLM.
A token is not always a word.
Computers understand numbers, not text.
Text is tokenized before being processed.
Tokenization is the first step in every LLM pipeline.



# Types of Tokenization

1. Character Tokenization ---> Very small tokens but long sequences.
2.  Word Tokenization -->Simple but struggles with unseen words.
3. Subword Tokenization (Used by LLMs) -->Most modern LLMs use subword tokenization because it balances vocabulary size and flexibility.


# Popular Tokenizers

- Byte Pair Encoding (BPE)
- WordPiece
- SentencePiece

For OpenAI models, BPE-based tokenization is commonly used.

You don't need to implement these algorithms for a 1-year interview, but you should know their names and purpose.

# Why Tokens Matter

Tokens affect:

- API cost
- Context window
- Model performance
- Latency


